# Vue Query Test Patterns

## NEVER assert on fetch URLs or Authorization headers in composable tests

**Do not write tests that assert `fetch` was called with a specific URL or header.**
These tests are unreliable in the Vue Query test environment and have failed every single time.
If you are tempted to write `expect(fetch).toHaveBeenCalledWith('/api/...')`, stop — delete it.
The query key tests already prove which URL will be used.

```js
// ❌ BANNED — never write this
expect(fetch).toHaveBeenCalledWith('/api/instructors/1', expect.any(Object))
expect(fetch).toHaveBeenCalledWith(expect.any(String), expect.objectContaining({ headers: ... }))
```

```js
// ✅ INSTEAD — test the query key, which determines the URL
const q = queryClient.getQueryCache().getAll()
    .find(q => q.queryKey[0] === 'instructors')
expect(q?.queryKey).toEqual(['instructors', 1])
```

## NEVER auto-trigger queries with flushPromises

Vue Query does NOT automatically execute queries on mount in the test environment — neither in
composable wrapper tests nor in full component tests. `flushPromises()` alone will NOT cause the
queryFn to run. Use the exposed `refetch*()` method instead.

If a component does not expose a `refetch*()` method, do not write a test that depends on
query data being loaded. Delete those tests — they will never work and are not worth fixing.

```js
// ❌ BAD — fetch will not be called, data will remain undefined
fetch.mockResolvedValueOnce(mockOk(data))
wrapper = mount(Comp)
await flushPromises()
expect(wrapper.vm.result.data.value).toBe(data)
```

```js
// ✅ GOOD — set up mock, then explicitly call refetch
wrapper = mount(Comp)
fetch.mockResolvedValueOnce(mockOk(data))
await wrapper.vm.result.refetchSomething()
expect(wrapper.vm.result.data.value).toBe(data)
```

## ALWAYS unmount component wrappers in afterEach

Failing to unmount leaves Vue Query observers active. When `queryClient.clear()` runs, stale
observers fire background refetches that consume `mockResolvedValueOnce` values meant for the
next test, leaving subsequent tests in a permanent loading state.

```js
// ✅ GOOD — track wrapper at describe scope, unmount in afterEach
describe('MyComponent', () => {
    let wrapper

    afterEach(() => {
        wrapper?.unmount()
        queryClient.clear()
    })

    const mountComp = (props) => {
        wrapper = mount(MyComponent, { ... })
        return wrapper
    }
})
```

## Synchronous throws vs async rejects

If a composable function throws synchronously (not returning a rejected promise),
use `expect(() => ...).toThrow()` not `await expect(...).rejects.toThrow()`.

```js
// ❌ BAD — will fail if the throw is synchronous
await expect(wrapper.vm.result.update({ bio: 'x' })).rejects.toThrow('...')

// ✅ GOOD
expect(() => wrapper.vm.result.update({ bio: 'x' })).toThrow('...')
```
